~ lazarillo
Blind: Come closer, boy... though perhaps it is better if you keep one hand upon your coin purse.

Blind: People pity the blind, yet I have seen more of men than those blessed with perfect sight.

Blind: The world teaches through hunger, trickery, and bruises. No book ever sharpened a wit half so well as an empty stomach.

Blind: Lázaro learned that lesson at my side, though not without complaint. Ah, the little rogue thought himself clever enough to outplay his own master.

Blind: But every cunning servant forgets one thing: the first lesson is always the hardest.

Blind: If you seek your escape, think not of nobles or priests.
Blind: Return instead to the beginning — to the master who opened the boy’s eyes before the world ever could.

=> END

~ metamorphosis
Gregor Samsa: The day begins the same way every day begins now: with a body that does not quite obey memory.

Gregor Samsa: I hear footsteps beyond the door. They hesitate, as if hesitation could restore what has already been decided.

Gregor Samsa: Once, I measured time by obligations. Now I measure it by the distance between sounds — the scrape of wood, the silence after my name is spoken incorrectly.

Gregor Samsa: They still talk about me. Not with me. That difference is the entire shape of my existence."*

Gregor Samsa: I try to respond, but meaning does not travel well through what I have become. Words arrive too late, already translated into something less than recognition.

Gregor Samsa: And yet, I understand them more clearly than ever before: what is not named as human slowly stops being treated as such.

Gregor Samsa: If there is a way out, it is not in remembering the life before this one. It is in recognizing the process itself...

Gregor Samsa: the slow deshumanization.
=> END

~ tomsawyer
Tom Sawyer: Well now, escaping a room ain’t so different from getting out of school on a hot summer day — it mostly takes imagination... and a little dishonesty.

Tom Sawyer: Folks always thought Huck and I were trouble, but trouble’s just another word for adventure when you’re young enough.

Tom Sawyer: We searched for pirates’ gold, wandered through caves, and even stood before our own funeral just to hear what people thought of us.

Tom Sawyer: But the strangest thing about adventure is this: the important part usually starts before anyone realizes they’re in danger.

Tom Sawyer: If you’re looking for the right answer, don’t think about the treasure at the end. Think about the boy who convinced everyone that work could be fun.

Tom Sawyer: That’s where his story truly begins.
